  "notes": [
    "The following transfer screening policy takes effect in fall 2024 and will be mandatory for all transfer students entering UC Santa Cruz fall 2026 and later. Transfer students entering UCSC prior to fall 2026 are encouraged to complete these requirements, but are not required to meet them. ﻿ ﻿ Earth Sciences B.S. Transfer Admission Screening Policy Transfer students must complete one of the following courses, or its articulated equivalent, with a grade of C (2.0) or better by the end of the spring term prior to transferring in the fall: MATH 11A – Calculus with Applications MATH 19A – Calculus for Science, Engineering, and Mathematics Refer to the \"Required Major Preparation Courses\" section below for lists of courses approved to fulfill these requirements. Strongly Recommended Major Preparation In addition to the required courses listed above, transfer students are strongly advised to complete the courses listed in the \"Recommended Preparation\" section below. These courses are prerequisites for upper-division courses required for the major. Students who do not complete these preparatory courses before transferring will likely need additional quarters of enrollment to complete their degree. Please visit the Earth & Planetary Sciences website to learn more about this major.",
    "All transfer applicants must satisfy University of California admissions eligibility requirements and campus admission selection criteria. All admission requirements must be completed by the end of spring prior to transfer. For more information on UC admissions eligibility requirements and admission to UC Santa Cruz, please visit the Admissions website . The UC Santa Cruz Transfer Admission Guarantee (TAG) is a formal agreement that ensures your fall admission to your chosen major, provided you are transferring from a California Community College and meet specific requirements. Visit the UC Santa Cruz TAG webpage for more information.",
    "THIS IS A SCREENING MAJOR. Screening majors require the completion of specific preparatory courses and/or minimum GPA requirements. For detailed information about the screening requirements for this major, please refer to \"Transfer Admission Screening Policy\" below. Additional preparatory coursework listed in the “Recommended Preparation” section are not required for admission, but are strongly recommended. Completion of these courses will help ensure timely progress toward degree completion. More information and a list of screening majors and non-screening majors may be found on the Admissions website.",
    "The UC Santa Cruz Advanced Placement (AP), International Baccalaureate (IB), and A-Level examination credit policies may be found in the UC Santa Cruz General Catalog . AP, IBH, and A-level exams may or may not satisfy course requirements, depending on the specific exam.",
    "Prior to July 1, 2023, UC Santa Cruz's General Chemistry series was offered as Chemistry 1A, 1B and 1C, with associated laboratories Chemistry 1M and 1N. Starting in the 2023-2024 academic year, this series was replaced by two new distinct series: Chemistry 3A, 3B and 3C, with labs Chemistry 3BL and 3CL; and Chemistry 4A and 4B with labs Chemistry 4AL and 4BL. Prospective transfer students who started working toward the Chemistry 1 series prior to the 2024-2025 academic year may complete equivalent courses as originally approved, and their articulated coursework will fulfill General Chemistry course requirements for this major. It is strongly recommended that community college students complete all General Chemistry coursework for their intended major at one institution prior to transfer to UC Santa Cruz."
